'en', 'pageNumber': 0, 'inputText': 'Have any questions? Please give us a call at 520-625-5511 Copyright © • Wick Communications Terms of Use | Privacy Policy Assistant Editor The Town of Sahuarita found significant support for a single contracted garbage collection service among residents who responded to a survey last fall. The town this week reported 66% of 723 respondents selected “very supportive” to the question, followed by 19% at “somewhat supportive”; 6% “neutral”; 5% “very unsupportive”; and 3% choosing “do not support.” Sahuarita’s population was 35,638 as of July 2022, the latest U.S. Census figures available. At four people per household, the survey reached about 12 percent of the town\'s population, assuming just one person per household answered the survey. Madera Highlands, a planned community in Sahuarita, moved to one trash hauling company in 2018 despite pushback from many residents. But not all households made the move to Republic Services, and several residents are are still served by other companies. The town said the fall survey screened respondents’ location, ensuring they lived in Sahuarita. The 12-week survey closed Nov. 17. While the survey found significant support for community-wide contracted service, it also found 32% of respondents were “satisfied” with their current service, followed by 27% selecting “neutral” and 22% saying they were “very satisfied.” The survey found low responses for residents unhappy with their current service, with 13% selecting “dissatisfied” and 6% choosing “very dissatisfied.” The town also reported Sahuarita residents pay $13 to $23 more per month for solid waste service than other Arizona municipalities with organized collection. The town listed nine jurisdictions ranging from populations of less than 10,000 to some with slightly more than 100,000 residents. The most similar sized community, El Mirage in the Phoenix metro area with about 36,000 people, has monthly rates of $18.52 compared to Sahuarita residents’ $38.38. The results are part of a larger discussion that will go before the council with no date set yet, a town spokeswoman said. In October, Sahuarita Public Works Director Galo Galovale told the Green Valley News and Sahuarita Sun the survey marked the first steps into gauging what residents want and possible future solid waste collection options. The town doesn’t have a dedicated solid waste department, leaving residents to rely on multiple private trash collection companies providing service within the same neighborhoods and traveling the same roads. At the time, Galovale said the wear and tear on streets was a major concern for the town. "We\'re seeing pavement failure because of the heavy truckloads," he said. "So, we\'re just trying to see how we can make sure that we\'re not spending a lot of our HURF funds in those kinds of repairs — making sure that we have our infrastructure in good shape." Counties and municipalities receive shares of Highway User Revenue Funds, HURF, from the state. During the survey, Galovale said the town was in the research phase of improving solid waste collection, saying the results could bring no changes; discussing the findings with current providers; or taking a plan for an in-depth study of a single-provider service to the Town Council. 'version': '2025-01-09-base', 'language': 'en', 'pageNumber': 0, 'inputText': 'Abundant sunshine. High 103F. Winds SW at 10 to 15 mph.. Clear skies. Low 72F. Winds SSW at 10 to 15 mph. Updated: June 1, 2024 @ 12:29 pm West Valley mayors pose with Gov. Katie Hobbs at the Phoenix Raceway. Two days after delivering her second State of the State address to launch the legislative year, Gov. Katie Hobbs came to the West Valley on Jan. 10. She spoke before a crowd of around 600 at the Phoenix Raceway during a WESTMARC-sponsored luncheon event for fellow elected officials, community leaders and media. Avondale Mayor Kenn Weise kicked things off, thanking the governor for her continued efforts to work with West Valley communities. After being introduced by WESTMARC President and CEO Sintra Hoffman and Phoenix Raceway President Latasha Causey, Hobbs gave her 35-minute speech. She began by summarizing the main issues she wanted to address, including securing the southern border, creating more jobs for working-class residents, dealing with the housing crisis, preserving Arizona’s water future, ensuring the quality and safety of schools, and making sure health care remains accessible to those who need it. The first issue Hobbs discussed was what she described as the “failure” of the federal government in securing the southern border. “When my fellow Arizonans gave me the honor of this office, I pledged to not play the same old political games that created this crisis and that have continually hurt communities, families and our state,” Hobbs said. She went on to detail how her administration took the “extraordinary step” of sending the National Guard for additional security following the closing of the Lukeville port of entry. In addition to awarding $84 million to help border communities manage the influx of migrants, Hobbs mentioned the creation of Operation SECURE within the Arizona Department of Homeland Security. “This session, I’m seeking ongoing funding to better coordinate our border response and continue fighting this humanitarian, economic and enforcement crisis. This new funding will expand the Operation with critical investments in border security, as well as resources to intercept the flow of fentanyl,” Hobbs said. The governor discussed the Arizona job market strength — saying that more residents were employed than at any point in the state’s history. Arizona also attracted more than $32 billion in foreign investment. “That $32 billion means jobs, jobs and more jobs for working people in Arizona. We created over 56,000 jobs in 2023. And we’re just getting started,” Hobbs said. As a magnet for high-tech and manufacturing businesses, she attested that Arizona leads the way in “building our nation’s future.” Hobbs also discussed how employment programs like Future48 and the BuilditAZ Apprenticeship Initiative are helping ready residents to fulfill jobs in those industries. “With our investments in Future48 workforce accelerators, we will prepare thousands of Arizonans every year for jobs building our nation’s future in industries like semiconductors, renewable energy, and aerospace and defense,” Hobbs said. Just as she highlighted the state’s strong job market, the governor didn’t shy away from addressing the ongoing housing affordability crisis. “Our housing affordability crisis has erased feelings of prosperity for too many,” Hobbs said. She said her administration worked to alleviate the pressure on Arizonans in 2023. “This past year, I worked with many here to find new and effective ways to address this issue,” Hobbs said. “We directed $150 million to keep more Arizonans housed through rental assistance programs, allocated money to provide access to legal aid for up to 1 million more Arizonans who are facing eviction or housing instability, and made a historic investment to create more housing that’s actually affordable for middle-class families.” This included the unveiling of the Arizona is Home Mortgage Assistance Program. “This program will help working-class families throughout the state with down payment assistance and mortgage interest rate relief,” Hobbs said. “That means a family of four living in Phoenix making up to $75,000 a year will have the opportunity to purchase a quality, affordable home.” Hobbs discussed the hot-button issue of Arizona’s water future. While the state currently uses less water per year than in the mid-1950s, she urged the audience that this was no time to relax. Those in violation of their water privileges need to be held accountable and Arizona must work collaboratively — within and outside the state — to ensure our water future is secure. “There is no better example of this than the agreement I negotiated earlier this year with our neighbors, Nevada and California, to conserve at least 3 million acre-feet of water — enough for 9 million homes — by 2026,” Hobbs said. She touted the agreement as both standing up to the federal government and safeguarding Arizona’s natural resources. Hobbs then moved on to discuss the state of Arizona’s education system. She applauded efforts by legislators for the passage of the Aggregate Expenditure Limit, which promised to keep schools open and students learning. “In addition to the AEL override, we also worked together to find bipartisan solutions to further support our public schools — including a $300 million infusion for K-12 schools,” Hobbs said. She also insisted on raises for teachers, improving school safety, addressing abuse of the state’s Empowerment Scholarship Account program and the expansion of university medical schools for the next generation of health care professionals. WESTMARC Board of Directors poses with Gov. Katie Hobbs at the Phoenix Raceway. The governor wrapped up her address with an overview of the state’s health care system. This included putting into place support systems for families dealing with childhood illness. “No family should have to go bankrupt to care for a sick child,” Hobbs said. “To combat this disturbing trend, we expanded KidsCare eligibility for thousands of Arizona children — enabling them to receive the care they need whether it’s routine checkups or lifesaving procedures without forcing their parents into mountains of debt or heartbreaking GoFundMe campaigns.” Part of this also included driving down the price of prescription drugs. With the creation of the Prescription Drug Affordability Division, prices for commonly used drugs like insulin will be better protected from price hikes. “These measures will help every Arizonan and ensure no one ever has to choose between paying for rent or paying for lifesaving medication,” Hobbs said. Finally, Hobbs delivered an ardent response to her stance on reproductive health care decisions. “I speak for millions of Arizonans with a clear message: These deeply personal decisions should be made between a woman and her doctor — not politicians and the government,” Hobbs said. “I will always defend Arizonans’ freedoms, and I refuse to back down in the face of those who want to criminalize doctors and outlaw abortion. That’s not happening on my watch.” This included calling for the repeal of the 1864 abortion ban, passing the Right to Contraception Act, and stopping the government from collecting and publishing data on every abortion in Arizona. “As I have said before and will continue to say again and again, reproductive freedom is not a partisan issue,” Hobbs said. “Women deserve to have access to the health care we need, we deserve to have our individual rights protected, and we deserve to make the personal decisions we deem best for ourselves and our families.” Hobbs ended her State of the State address to the West Valley by reminding everyone in the audience of what they all had in common. “We are bound by our love for this state, from its beautiful forests and mountains to its breathtaking vistas and stunning natural beauty,” Hobbs said. “And we are bound by our responsibility to ensure every person who calls this place home has the opportunity to succeed today — as well as the generations who follow us.” Never miss an issue. An insider’s guide to where to eat, sleep, shop, explore area attractions, hike the best trails and sightsee in Williams, the Grand Canyon and northern Arizona. Click to view in 3D! The Grand Canyon isn’t just spectacular — it’s one of the seven natural wonders of the world, along with Mount Everest in Nepal, Victoria Falls in Zambia/Zimbabwe, Australia’s Great Barrier Reef, the Northern Lights, Paricutin Volcano in Mexico and Harbor of Rio de Janeiro in Brazil. The Canyon attracts 4.5 million visitors from all over the world annually. Click to view in 3D! Williams, Arizona was first settled in 1874. Cool summers, a colorful fall and sunny, white winters, make Williams a playground for all seasons. Downtown Williams is listed in the National Register of Historic Places, with most of the buildings constructed in the early 1900s. There are seven lakes and reservoirs within an 18-mile radius of Williams. No matter what time of year, visitors to Williams will always find something fun going on. Whether you’re arriving by car, train, plane or bicycle Williams is a year-round destination allowing visitors great weather to hike, shop and explore. A life of adventure starts with you. Deciding to explore a new town or one of the Seven Natural Wonders of the World could be the first step in a series of once-in-a-lifetime experiences. Don’t miss out on these opportunities for adventure and exploration! Want to advertise with us? Call (928) 635-4426 Take a look at new statistics and learn more about the Grand Canyon/Williams area. The $935,000 advanced fire truck is designed to enhance its capacity to safeguard residents and property during emergencies. “The acquisition of these cutting-edge firefighting vehicles underscores the town’s commitment to maintaining a high level of emergency response readiness,” said Madisyn Garrett, Carefree’s communications manager, in a statement. High 102F. Winds SW at 10 to 15 mph.. A clear sky. Low around 75F. Winds SW at 10 to 15 mph. Updated: June 1, 2024 @ 12:29 pm The Governor’s Office of Highway Safety recently awarded the Peoria Police Department $189,721 in grants to help increase DUI enforcement, traffic enforcement and education in and around Peoria. Each of the grants allows the department to conduct additional enforcement throughout the fiscal year by participating in saturation patrols and selective traffic enforcement details focusing on speeding, red-light running and DUI enforcement. In addition, some of these grants will allow the Peoria Police Department to purchase equipment that will assist in the reconstruction of serious injury and fatal collision investigations. The department will use $42,827 of the grant funds to continue to improve the enforcement of traffic safety laws intended to reduce death, injury, property damage and promote roadway safety, along with deterring aggressive and distracted drivers. The funds will also provide for continuing education that increases the public’s awareness associated with the dangers of speeding and aggressive/distracted driving, as well as continue to provide training and updates on traffic laws to officers. The department will utilize $83,240 of the grant funds to reduce impaired driving, which is a high-priority objective for Arizona. Effective enforcement is an essential countermeasure to reducing DUI offenses and the deadly crashes that can be associated with impaired drivers. Driving while under the influence can carry a hefty price tag, including criminal and legal expenses, property damage and, more importantly, death. Peoria will use $22,309 of the grant funds to promote motorcycle safety in and around the city. This funding will allow Peoria police motorcycle officers to provide instruction to intermediate riders and further promote safe riding habits. Two motorcycle safety courses will be offered for free to the riding public this year. Officers will continue to address motorcycle safety through education and enforcement utilizing these funds. Peoria police will utilize $35,313 to help increase pedestrian, school zone, school bus and bicycle safety in the city. This funding will allow Peoria police officers to focus their time on making the roadways safe for pedestrians. The Peoria Police Department plans to utilize grant funding for overtime enforcement and provide educational awareness about the traffic laws and safety rules in these areas. This grant will also allow the department to continue its Bicycle Safety Partnership by providing instruction to grade school students as well as hosting multiple Bicycle Safety Rodeos throughout the city. The final $6,032 will go toward purchasing equipment and training on it regarding the reconstruction of serious injury and fatal traffic collisions. This evidence is an essential part of the reconstruction and helps investigators better understand the circumstances that led up to and had an aspect in the collision. This funding will allow Peoria police officers to provide a multi-faceted approach to traffic safety through education, deterrence and aggressive enforcement of our state traffic and DUI laws. Un portavoz del Partido Republicano de Arizona confirmó la cancelación a The Arizona Republic el jueves por la tarde. El motivo del cambio de planes no quedó claro de inmediato. Se había programado que Trump realizara un mitin en la iglesia Dream City en el norte de Phoenix como parte del evento Freedom Fest del Partido Republicano de Arizona. "El presidente Trump estará en Nueva York para asistir a la corte el viernes y no podrá asistir al evento, pero regresará a Arizona lo antes posible", dijo Jason Miller, asesor principal de la campaña de Trump, en una declaración escrita proporcionada al Republic. "Esperamos ganar Arizona para el presidente Trump, elegir a (la candidata al Senado) Kari Lake y trabajar con el AZGOP para lograrlo". Trump dio un breve testimonio el jueves en el juicio. La cancelación se produce un día después de que DeWit, presidente del partido, dimitiera tras la publicación de una grabación de audio de marzo de 2023 en la que ofrecía a Kari Lake un trabajo lucrativo para mantenerse fuera de la carrera por el Senado de Estados Unidos. Lake rechazó lo que ella caracterizó como un soborno. En su renuncia, DeWit dijo que "el equipo de Lake" amenazó con publicar otra grabación más dañina. En comentarios a NBC News, DeWit dijo que había dudas generalizadas sobre la viabilidad electiva de Lake. Tanto DeWit como Lake se encuentran entre los leales a Trump más destacados en Arizona. Su desacuerdo deja al Partido Republicano de Arizona repentinamente buscando un nuevo líder y se produce cuando DeWit estaba tratando de reconstruir su base financiera, algo que una visita de Trump podría haber ayudado. En cambio, el partido enfrenta nuevas preguntas antes de su reunión anual del sábado. DeWit dejó en claro en su renuncia que esperaba permanecer en su puesto hasta recibir lo que consideraba una amenaza del equipo de Lake. "He decidido no correr el riesgo", escribió DeWit. "Renuncio como solicitó Lake, con la esperanza de que cumpla su compromiso de cesar sus ataques". Horas más tarde, Lake le dijo a una audiencia en línea que los esfuerzos de DeWit eran "repugnantes", pero no explicó por qué esperó hasta esta semana para publicar la grabación y su campaña sostuvo que nadie allí intentó chantajear a DeWit. La cancelación también se produce en un momento en que Trump buscaba generar impulso para una campaña electoral general después de su victoria en el caucus de Iowa y las primarias de New Hampshire. Trump testificó brevemente en Nueva York el jueves en un caso para evaluar los daños y perjuicios en su contra por continuar difamando a E. Jean Carroll, la mujer que lo demandó exitosamente por agredirla sexualmente en la década de 1990. Los alegatos finales en ese caso están programados para el viernes. El reportero Ray Stern contribuyó a esta historia.'}]
